div.p:
A redox-active electrolyte supercapacitor (RAES) is a promising system that increases the energy density of a supercapacitor by providing additional pseudocapacitance, which arises from an inserted redox couple in an electrolyte. However, the energy density of RAESs is still considerably low for practical applications, and enhancing the operating voltage window as well as the capacitance of RAESs is very necessary. In this study, we rationally designed a nonaqueous redox-active electrolyte mainly on the basis of the relative position of the electrochemical stability window of a supporting electrolyte and the redox potential of a redox couple. Therefore, the judicious combination of a redox pair, decamethylcobaltocene/decamethylcobaltocenium, and a supporting electrolyte, 1-ethyl-3-methylimidazolium bis(trifluoromethylsulfonyl)imide dissolved in adiponitrile, not only provides additional capacitance from a faradaic redox reaction (21.3 → 57.1 F g

 –1

) but also extends the operating voltage window to almost the entire electrochemical stability window of the supporting electrolyte (3.1 V). A carbon-nanotube-based RAES exhibits outstanding performance, including improved energy density (75.6 Wh kg

 –1

), compared to previously reported nonaqueous RAESs. Our systematic approach might play a crucial role in the further development of high-performance nonaqueous RAESs.

Figure 1. Scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of (a) single-walled carbon nanotube (SWNT) and (b) carbon paper (CP). (c) Schematic of two-electrode cell configuration and (d) molecular structures of redox-active electrolyte composed of decamethylcobaltocene (DmCc), decamethylcobaltocenium hexafluorophosphate (DmCcPF

 6

), 1-ethyl-3-methylimidazolium bis(trifluoromethylsulfonyl)imide (EMImTFSI), and adiponitrile (ADN). (e) XPS survey, (f) C 1s scan, and (g) Raman spectra of SWNT.

Figure 2. Electrochemical stable voltage window of supporting electrolyte, EMImTFSI in ADN (scan rate = 20 mV s

 –1

).

div.div:
We successfully demonstrated the insertion of rationally chosen redox molecules into nonaqueous electrolytes to produce high-energy-density supercapacitors. The elaborately designed redox-active electrolyte could extend the cell operating voltage up to nearly the entire electrochemical stability window (3.1 V) of the supporting electrolyte and also increase the cell capacitance (21.3 → 57.1 F g

 –1

) because of the additional faradaic process. The enhancement in operation voltage window and cell capacitance led to a considerably higher energy density (75.6 Wh kg

 –1

) than previously reported for nonaqueous RAESs. Moreover, the supercapacitor with the organic redox-active electrolyte exhibited long-term cycle stability (98.8% over 8000 cycles at 5 A g

 –1

) because of the highly reversible redox reaction of DmCc/DmCc

 +

, possibly originating from its chemically stable molecular structure. We believe that our approach of rational selection of electrolyte components has great potential for developing high-energy-density nonaqueous RAESs.

